__data__.text: The Hells Angels Motorcycle Club (HAMC) established chapters in Anchorage and Fairbanks, Alaska in December 1982.
The HAMC merged with the Brothers Motorcycle Club (Brothers MC) in December 1982.
The Brothers MC was formed in 1967.
The Brothers MC had an association with the Hells Angels in California's San Francisco Bay Area by 1977.

Anthony John Tait was a sergeant-at-arms for the Anchorage Hells Angels chapter.
Anthony John Tait became a paid informant for the Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI) in 1985.
Anthony John Tait provided the government with detailed information on the club's organization and criminal activities for two years.
The criminal activities that Anthony John Tait provided information on included drugs and explosives trafficking.
During the investigation, Anthony John Tait travelled the country at government expense to meet with various Hells Angels members.
Anthony John Tait covertly recorded some of these meetings by wearing a wire.
As part of the investigation, the informant and undercover agents purchased approximately $1.6 million of cocaine and methamphetamine from the Hells Angels.
The informant and undercover agents also purchased more than twenty pounds of explosives, three automatic weapons and two silencers from the Hells Angels.

The Organized Crime Drug Enforcement Task Force (OCDETF) Operation CACUS culminated with 38 HAMC members in Alaska and four other states being arrested on narcotics, weapons, explosives and conspiracy charges on November 10, 1987.

In 2001, Cynthia Yvonne Garcia was murdered by Hells Angels members Kevin J. Augustiniak, Michael Christopher "Mesa Mike" Kramer, and Paul Merle Eischeid.
Garcia was a forty-four-year-old mother of six.
The murder occurred during a party at the Hells Angels' clubhouse in Mesa.
